   <text>
      <body>
         <div type="letter">
            <pb n="1" facs="Edgeworth_Huntington_HM 28600_1820_08_17_page01.jpg"/>
            <opener>
               With truth my very dear <persName ref="./Personography.xml#BeauF1">Beaufort</persName> I assure you that I have<lb/>
               this day enjoyed a sweet species of pleasure from <unclear>hearing</unclear> some who are near and dear to<lb/>
               You <unclear></unclear>under my roof- My beloved Wife and children are, Thank God, quite well <unclear></unclear>We are<lb/>
               <unclear></unclear> enjoying<unclear></unclear> in this <unclear></unclear> country - <unclear></unclear>to this to<lb/>
               <unclear></unclear> the same for yourself &amp; taken in as<unclear></unclear>your<unclear>faithful &amp; </unclear><unclear></unclear><lb/>               
               <dateline>
                  <date when="1820-08-17"/><hi rend="underline">Aug<hi rend="superscript">st</hi>. 17<hi rend="superscript">h</hi>. 1820</hi> --<lb/></dateline>  
            </opener>
            <p>My dear <persName ref="./Personography.xml#BeauF1">Francis</persName> I write to you on your<lb/>
               friend <persName ref="./Personography.xml#HillJ1">Captain Hillyar</persName>'s writing desk<lb/>
               in a delightfully pleasant room in<lb/>
               the house in which he resides at <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Yverdon-les-Bains_SZ"><choice><orig>Yver<lb/>
                  -dun</orig><reg>Yverdon</reg></choice></placeName> <add>on the banks of the <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Lac-de-Neuchâtel_SZ">lake of Neufchatel</placeName>.</add> Hearing that we had arrived here<lb/>
               &amp; that we were going to see <persName ref="./Personography.xml#PestJ1">Pestalozzi</persName>'s<lb/>
               establishment he and M<hi rend="superscript">rs</hi>. <persName ref="./Personography.xml#HillM1">Hillyar</persName><lb/>
               went there to meet us. - You may guess<lb/>
               how glad we were to see the friend to<lb/>
               whom we know you are so much <choice><orig>attach<lb/>
                  ed</orig><reg>attached</reg></choice> &amp; to hear the name of <persName ref="./Personography.xml#BeauF1">Beaufort</persName> so far<lb/>
               from home pronounced with so much<lb/>
               affection. He introduced your little <choice><orig>God-<lb/>
                  son</orig><reg>godson</reg></choice> to us - we heard him go through a<lb/>
               mathematical demonstration in his<lb/>
               class at <persName ref="./Personography.xml#PestJ1">Pestalozzi</persName>'s clearly - he is a fine<lb/>
               stout looking boy with great power of<lb/>
               attention. - Capt<hi rend="superscript">n</hi>. <persName ref="./Personography.xml#HillJ1">Hylliar</persName> &amp; his gentle<lb/>
               obliging <persName ref="./Personography.xml#HillM1">wife</persName> <unclear>invited</unclear> not only myself<lb/>
               and your two <choice><orig>neices</orig><reg>nieces</reg></choice>, but all our party<lb/>
               here <persName ref="./Personography.xml#MoilJ1">M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>.</persName> and <persName ref="./Personography.xml#MoilA1">M<hi rend="superscript">rs</hi>. Moilliet</persName> &amp; their <persName ref="./Personography.xml#BissM1">two</persName> <lb/>
               <persName ref="./Personography.xml#SmitS2">daughters</persName> - I frankly accepted the <choice><orig>inten-<lb/>
                  -tion</orig><reg>intention</reg></choice> for it was so cordially given I could<lb/>
               not bear to refuse it and to lose this only<lb/>
               opportunity of spending an hour or two<lb/>
               with your friend - He appears to me<lb/>
               one of the best and happiest tempered<lb/>
               men alive - enjoying every thing and<lb/>
               thanking God for whatever other people<lb/>
               
               <pb n="2" facs="Edgeworth_Huntington_HM 28600_1820_08_17_page02.jpg"/>
               
               might think a small comparitive portion<lb/>
               of what are called the blessings of life -<lb/>
               He has the first floor of an admirable<lb/>
               house &amp; what do you think he pays for it<lb/>
               4 good bedrooms - 2 sittings rooms, &amp; a good<lb/>
               kitchen with a servants room <del>&amp; a good cellar</del><lb/>
               <del>to go to</del> &amp; a good garden to walk in all for<lb/>
               fifty pounds English a year. - The family<lb/>
               to whom the house belongs are most kind<lb/>
               to them, taking care of their children as far<lb/>
               as they wish it - and no more - and <choice><orig>afford-<lb/>
                  ing</orig><reg>affording</reg></choice> them every possible assistance &amp; <choice><orig>conve-<lb/>
                     ience</orig><reg>convenience</reg></choice> in the common affairs of life - For<lb/>
               instance an excellent cellar open to them on<lb/>
               the most reasonable terms - as <persName ref="./Personography.xml#HillJ1">Capt<hi rend="superscript">n</hi>. H</persName> tells<lb/>
               "me he longs for <persName ref="./Personography.xml#BeauF1">Beaufort</persName> to know all these<lb/>
               "things and yet cannot bring himself to<lb/>
               "sit down to write such trifles to such a<lb/>
               "superior being" I determined to do it directly<lb/>
               - I have seen Capt<hi rend="superscript">n</hi> <persName ref="./Personography.xml#HillJ1">Hillyar</persName>’s 4 children HillJ2 James <add>Beaufort</add> 12 years old, <persName ref="./Personography.xml#BissM1">Mary</persName> 5 –<lb/>
               <persName ref="./Personography.xml#HillC1">Charles</persName> 3 and <persName ref="./Personography.xml#HillH1">Henry</persName> 15 months old – fine healthy happy children<lb/></p>
               <p>Before I met or at least before I knew<lb/>
                  who Capt<hi rend="superscript">n</hi> <persName ref="./Personography.xml#HillJ1">Hillyar</persName> was, I had <add>just</add> determined<lb/>
                  to write to you about your brother <persName ref="./Personography.xml#BeauW1">William</persName> about<lb/>
               an establishment for the deaf and dumb<lb/>
               which I went to see here - I have not time<lb/>
               to write two letters; will you be so kind<lb/>
               to tell him that I have been much pleased<lb/>
               with what I have seen of M. <persName ref="./Personography.xml#NaefX1">Naef</persName> - whose <choice><orig>pros-<lb/>
               -pectus</orig><reg>prospectus</reg></choice> I enclose - I went in to his house<lb/>
               quite unexpectedly and saw about 9 <del>dozen</del><lb/>
               of his pupils from 8 to 14 - their <choice><orig>counte-<lb/>
               -nances</orig><reg>countenances</reg></choice> shewed that they were kindly treated<lb/>
               - In eight months one of them a boy of eleven<lb/>
               years old has learned to speak <hi rend="underline"> intelligibly </hi><lb/>
               - I do not mean fluently - His voice, &amp; the<lb/>
               voices of all whom I heard speak were less harsh<lb/>
               &amp; disagreeable than any I ever heard from the<lb/>
               
               <pb n="3" facs="Edgeworth_Huntington_HM 28600_1820_08_17_page03.jpg"/>
               
               pupils of other masters who profess to teach the<lb/>
               deaf and dumb to speak <add>I may say more their voices are agreeable</add> - <hi rend="underline">They</hi> read aloud quite<lb/>
               intelligibly - most of them are Germans - a<lb/>
                  few French - no English - <del>and</del> Mr <persName ref="./Personography.xml#NaefX1">Naef</persName> does<lb/>
               not understand English - But the same<lb/>
               methods by which he teaches one language<lb/>
               the pupil of course could learn any other!<lb/>
               - I saw <del>them</del> <add>one</add> cast up this sum with ease <del>in</del><lb/>
               4764 x 3460 x 2179 - he made 2 mistakes &amp; corrected<lb/>
               them when pointed out -<lb/></p>
               <p>The bedrooms are good - each child a <choice><orig>sepa-<lb/>
                  rate</orig><reg>separate</reg></choice> bed - large garden - &amp; various means<lb/>
               of amusement and bodily exercise under<lb/>
               the head Gymnastics - If your brother<lb/>
                  <persName ref="./Personography.xml#BeauW1">William</persName> should wish to send a boy here<lb/>
                  (a girl is out of the question) <persName ref="./Personography.xml#HillJ1">M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>.</persName> and <persName ref="./Personography.xml#HillA1">M<hi rend="superscript">rs</hi>. HIl-<lb/>
               lyar</persName> would attend to him constantly<lb/>
                  - They stay here <hi rend="underline">another year</hi> <add>for certain perhaps longer</add>- If <persName ref="./Personography.xml#BeauW1">William</persName><lb/>
               could send his boy to <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Paris_FR">Paris</placeName> I would<lb/>
               receive him &amp; find means of forwarding<lb/>
                  him to <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Geneva_SZ">Geneva</placeName> and from thence to <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Yverdon-les-Bains_SZ"><choice><orig>Yver<lb/>
                     -don</orig><reg>Yverdon</reg></choice></placeName> - The expense in the whole - <choice><orig>instruc<lb/>
                        -tion</orig><reg>instruction</reg></choice> boarding &amp; lodging is 50 Guineas a<lb/>
               year - the food is good &amp; sufficient as<lb/>
               the health of the boys shews - but it is<lb/>
               not luxurious - breakfast - soup - plain<lb/>
               meat &amp; vegetables at dinner - The religion<lb/>
                  in <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Yverdon-les-Bains_SZ">Yverdon</placeName> is protestant &amp; M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>. <persName ref="./Personography.xml#NaefX1">Naef</persName> is a<lb/>
               protestant - I shall be in <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Paris_FR">Paris</placeName> in the<lb/>
               2<hi rend="superscript">d</hi>. or 3.<hi rend="superscript">d</hi> week in October &amp; can be heard of always<lb/>
                  at the <persName ref="./Personography.xml#DeleE1">Delessert</persName>s - <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Rue-Coq-Heron_FR">Rue <choice><orig>Coqueron</orig><reg>Rue Coq-Heron</reg></choice></placeName> - At <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EmerX1">M.<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>: Emer<unclear>y</unclear></persName><lb/>
                  Black bear <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Picadilly-Circus_ENK">Piccadilly</placeName> there is a Swiss <unclear>voilure</unclear><lb/>
                  who would bring any person from <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#London_ENK">London</placeName><lb/>
                  to <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Yverdon-les-Bains_SZ"><choice><orig>Yverdun</orig><reg>Yverdon</reg></choice></placeName> for twelve pounds - He offered<lb/>
               a gentleman here to bring him 7 boys for<lb/>
               <add>£</add>10 each <add>in fourteen days</add> - all expenses cleared - &amp; he does not<lb/>
               starve them on the road - Now perhaps all<lb/>
               I have written may be quite useless but it will<lb/>
                  shew that <persName ref="./Personography.xml#BeauW1">William B</persName>'s interests are fresh in my mind<lb/>
               
               <pb n="4" facs="Edgeworth_Huntington_HM 28600_1820_08_17_page04.jpg"/>
               
                  <unclear></unclear> to <persName ref="./Personography.xml#PestJ1">Pestalozzi</persName> - he is almost past mental labors<lb/>
               -but others are carrying on his plans at his <choice><orig>establish<lb/>
                  ment</orig><reg>establishment</reg></choice> - M.<hi rend="superscript">r</hi> <persName ref="./Personography.xml#SchmX1">Schmidt</persName> <add>one of</add> his pupils teaches <choice><orig>mathe-<lb/>
                  matics</orig><reg>mathematics</reg></choice> well - exceedingly well as far as we<lb/>
               can judge by the clearness &amp; intelligence of his<lb/>
                     his pupils - M.<hi rend="superscript">r</hi> <persName ref="./Personography.xml#GreaX1">Greaves</persName> a gentleman who has been<lb/>
               here 2 years for no purpose but to learn the<lb/>
               system of teaching German &amp; English - Of German<lb/>
               he knew nothing! - He teaches <add>language</add> by shewing the <choice><orig>exter<lb/>
                  nal</orig><reg>external</reg></choice> objects first &amp; annexing the names at the moment<lb/>
               - then their qualities &amp; then their actions<lb/>
               - He tries to make the children invent the rules of<lb/>
               grammar from shewing them their use - The rev<hi rend="superscript">d</hi>. M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>. <unclear>Muzo</unclear><lb/>
                  from Oxford teaches Latin &amp; Greek and English for <persName ref="./Personography.xml#PestJ1">Pestalozzi</persName><lb/>
               on this plan - he is rather too full of words -<lb/>
               - I need say no more to You - there seems to be<lb/>
               a great inconvenience in the variety of the tongue<lb/>
                  spoken at <persName ref="./Personography.xml#PestJ1">Pestalozzi</persName>'s - The English is a <unclear>barbarous</unclear><lb/>
               jargon - The French bad - And the children and<lb/>
               their masters mix French English &amp; German <choice><orig>toge<lb/>
                  -ther</orig><reg></reg></choice> so that they will I fear speak none correctly<lb/>
               But what is worse their ideas seem confused in<lb/>
               this inaccuracy of language - Sum total - I would not<lb/>
                  for any consideration that <persName ref="./Personography.xml#BeauF2">Francis</persName> or one of your boys<lb/>
                  were at <persName ref="./Personography.xml#PestJ1">Pestalozzi</persName>'s for their education - But I<lb/>
               should be glad that they would learn mathematics<lb/>
               from M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>. <persName ref="./Personography.xml#SchmX1">Schmidt</persName> - provided that they could not learn them as<lb/>
